text.tspan: Larger body masses result in greater dispersal distances (e.g. Sutherland et al.
2000, Whitmee & Orme 2013; Stevens et al. 2014, Jenkins et al. 2007)
Animals that swim typically achieve the longest dispersal distances, with flying
species showing intermediate ranges, and running animals the shortest,
corresponding to energetic costs of movement (Alexander, 2003)
Carnivores will have greater dispersal distances as they have more mobile and
patchy resources, compared to omnivores and herbivores (Sutherland et al. 2000)
Migrants have physiological and morphological adaptations that enhance
movement capacity, leading to greater dispersal distances (Oâ€™Connor 1990;
Ramenofsky. 1990). Conversely, seasonal migratory movements can reduce the
need for dispersal by fulfilling similar spatial functions, such as locating future
Lower resource availability can drive greater dispersal distances, as individuals
must move farther to locate sufficient resources and suitable habitats
Higher productivity can increase local population density, intensifying competition
at the birth site and leading to greater dispersal distances as individuals move to
Higher seasonality is linked to more variable and unpredictable resources, which
leads to increased movement and larger home ranges in many species
(Killeen et al. 2014; Broekman et al. 2023). Similarly, we expect greater dispersal
distances with increasing seasonality, as species need to travel further to locate
In ectotherms, dispersal distance could be shaped by direct physiological and
behavioural responses to temperature; higher temperatures generally increase
activity and but the effect depends on the temperature gradient captured. In
endotherms, which regulate their own body temperature, may lead to a negative
effect of high temperatures on dispersal due to thermal stress or avoidance of
Human disturbance can lead to either shorter or greater dispersal distances.
Movement barriers, increased food availability, or the presence of refugia may
reduce dispersal by limiting the need for individuals to move far
(Venter et al. 2016). Conversely, habitat fragmentation or the alteration and loss
of suitable breeding habitats can increase dispersal distances as individuals are
forced to search for viable areas to settle (Haddad et al. 2015; Tucker et al. 2018)
Fish may show shorter dispersal distances in highly fragmented rivers due to
barriers like dams restricting movement (Rahel & McLaughlin. 2018). However,
when suitable habitat is scarce nearby, fish may disperse farther to find adequate
environments, as habitat shifts can force longer dispersal despite fragmentation
